
[1]displease

   DISPLEASE, v.t. displeze. [dis and please.]

   1. To offend; to make angry, sometimes in a slight degree. It usually
   expresses less than anger, vex, irritate and provoke. Applied to the
   Almighty in scripture, it may be considered as equivalent to anger.

   God was displeased with this thing; therefore he smote Israel. 1
   Chronicles 21.

   2. To disgust; to excite aversion in; as, acrid and rancid substances
   displease the taste.

   3. To offend; to be disagreeable to. A distorted figure displeases the
   eye.
